[ChapterName "Exercise 6: The crucial Lucena move"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/UsqmCsgC/fX8kAG8I"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "1K6/1P6/4k3/8/8/8/1r6/3R4 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2021.05.28"]
[UTCTime "21:55:06"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ The black king has just been forced two files away from our pawn. But how do we actually promote? }
1. Rd4! { Excellent, white begins building the bridge. } (1. Ra1 { Yes this move equally wins immediately. But let's work on "building the bridge" in this exercise. }) 1... Rb1 2. Kc7 (2. Ka7 { This move works equally well. Play Kc7 instead for the solution. }) 2... Rc1+ 3. Kb6 Rb1+ 4. Kc6 (4. Ka6 { This move works equally well. Play Kc6 instead for the solution. }) (4. Ka5?? { Oh no your pawn! } 4... Rxb7 $10) (4. Kc5?? { Oh no your pawn! } 4... Rxb7 $10) 4... Rc1+ 5. Kb5 Rb1+ 6. Rb4 $18 { After walking a tightrope, the white king is now safe from checks, and the pawn promotes next. } *


[Event "Tal Memorial"]
[Date "2006.11.12"]
[Round "6"]
[White "Levon Aronian"]
[Black "Magnus Carlsen"]
[Result "1-0"]
[WhiteElo "2741"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackElo "2698"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Intermediate Endgames You Must Know!"]
[ChapterName "Magnus Carlsen missing his chance"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/UsqmCsgC/JH6OUk7k"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "3R4/4K1k1/4P3/r7/8/8/8/8 b - - 0 71"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Levon Aronian has successfully stopped Magnus Carlsen from reaching the easy Philidor position. However, this is still drawn with best play as long as black can stop white from reaching the Lucena position. }
71... Ra7+ 72. Rd7 (72. Ke8 Kf6 73. Rd6 Re7+ 74. Kd8 Rxe6 $10 { Black immediately picks up the pawn in this line, and draws. }) 72... Ra8! 73. Rd6 Ra7+?? (73... Kg6! { Necessary. White has only 2 tries here, and neither of them make progress. } 74. Kd7 (74. Rd7 Kg7 $10 { Repeating the position from the game }) (74. Rd8 Ra7+ 75. Rd7 Ra8 $10 { Another repetition }) 74... Kf6 75. e7+ Kf7 { With control of the queening square, this is still drawn. } 76. Re6 Ra7+ 77. Kd8 Ra8+ $10) 74. Ke8! { In this position, Carlsen resigned. Both players realized that white has now achieved the Lucena position. The game could have continued: } 74... Ra8+ (74... Kf6 75. e7+ Kg7 76. Rd4! { Preparing for the Lucena position if black tries to get behind the passed pawn. } 76... Ra8+ 77. Kd7 Ra7+ 78. Ke6 Ra6+ 79. Rd6 $18 { These horizontal checks are handled easily. }) 75. Rd8 Ra1 76. e7 Re1 77. Rd2 Kf6 78. Rf2+ Kg7 $18 { Arriving at the Lucena position we've seen earlier. Indeed, even Super GMs need to know these endgames cold! } 1-0


